		<h1>Research</h1>

		<h2>Overview</h2> 
	
		  <p>My main research interest is the investigation of methods that simplify the design of objects&#39; appearance,
		  which comes from the interaction of surface materials and scene lighting, through the development of interactive
		  rendering algorithms and intuitive appearance design interfaces. This research led to various theoretical results
		  and practical applications in the areas of interactive realistic rendering, user interfaces and visual
		  perception. A comprehensive list of <a href="publications.php">publications</a> is available.</p> 
		  
		  <p>None of this research would have been possible without the help of my grad students (B. Kerr, X. An, J. Ou, J. Denning),
		  funding agencies (NSF, Intel, Google, Pixar, ISTS) and external collaborators (K. Bala, M. Hasan, J. Lawrence, 
		  A. Finkelstein, S. Rusinkiewicz, P. Peers, X. Tong, Y. Dong, J. Wang, R. Wang, W. Matusik).</p>
	
		<h2 class="vspace">Projects</h2> 
		
			  <h3>Intuitive appearance design</h3> 
	
			  <p class="novspaceafter">Designing appearance, i.e. material and lighting parameters, is cumbersome since current interfaces
			  require designers to specify algorithmic parameters that are only indirectly related to objects&#205;
			  appearance. My work investigates interfaces that allow users to effectively specify environments&#205; final
			  looks, and algorithms that automatically set the appearance parameters required to achieve users&#205;
			  goals. Related papers: </p>
			  
			  <ul> 
				<li><a href="publication.php?id=envylight10">EnvyLight: An Interface for Editing Natural Illumination</a></li> 
				<li><a href="publication.php?id=matstudy10">Toward Evaluating Material Design Interface Paradigms for Novice Users</a></li> 
				<li><a href="publication.php?id=bendylight10">BendyLights: Artistic Control of Direct Illumination by Curving Light Rays</a></li> 
				<li><a href="publication.php?id=scheat10">Visibility Editing For All-Frequency Shadow Design</a></li> 
				<li><a href="publication.php?id=ucct10">User Controllable Color Transfer</a></li>				
				<li><a href="">Toward Evaluating Lighting Design Interface Paradigms for Novice Users</a></li> 
				<li><a href="publication.php?id=subedit09">SubEdit: A Representation for Editing Measured Heterogeneous Subsurface Scattering</a></li> 
				<li><a href="publication.php?id=appprop08">AppProp: All-Pairs Appearance-Space Edit Propagation</a></li> 
				<li><a href="publication.php?id=icheat08">iCheat: A Representation for Artistic Control of Cinematic
				Realistic Lighting</a></li> 
				<li><a href="publication.php?id=appwand07">AppWand: Editing Measured Materials using Appearance-Driven
				Optimization</a></li> 
				<li><a href="publication.php?id=lpaint07">Lighting by Paint</a></li> 
				<li><a href="publication.php?id=shadowui02">A User Interface for Interactive Cinematic Shadow
				Design</a></li> 
				<li><a href="publication.php?id=gloss00">Toward a Psychophysically-based Light Reflection model for Image
				Synthesis</a></li> 
				<li><a href="publication.php?id=gloss01">A Psychophysically-Based Model of Surface Gloss Perception</a></li> 
			  </ul> 

			  <h3 class="vspace">Physical Appearance Reproduction</h3> 
	
			  <p class="novspaceafter">Today printing methods can reproduce the color and shapes of physical objects. 
			  This project investigates how to use current printing hardware to reproduce a large variety of
			  material appearance for opaque and translucent objects. Related papers:</p> 
	
			  <ul> 
				<li><a href="publication.php?id=bssrdfprint10">Fabricating Spatially-Varying Subsurface Scattering</a></li> 
				<li><a href="publication.php?id=brdfprint09">Printing Spatially-Varying Reflectance</a></li> 
			  </ul> 

			  <h3 class="vspace">Interactive appearance design</h3> 
	
			  <p class="novspaceafter">Interactive feedback is fundamental for efficient appearance design. While for simple scenes current
			  algorithms serves us well, I am particularly interested in guaranteeing interactivity while designing
			  materials and lighting in the globally-illuminated high-complexity environments, which remains problematic
			  for typical applications in architectural, cinematic and game lighting. Related papers:</p> 
			  <ul> 
				<li><a href="publication.php?id=safegi10">SafeGI: Type Checking to Improve Correctness in Rendering System Implementation</a></li> 
				<li><a href="publication.php?id=cuts08">Fast, Realistic Lighting and Material Design using Nonlinear Cut Approximation</a></li> 
				<li><a href="publication.php?id=temporal08">Tensor Clustering for Rendering Many-Light Animations</a></li> 
				<li><a href="publication.php?id=mxsmp07">Matrix Row-Column Sampling for the Many-Light Problem</a></li> 
				<li><a href="publication.php?id=dti06">Direct-to-Indirect Transfer for Cinematic Relighting</a></li> 
				<li><a href="publication.php?id=lod05">User-Configurable Automatic Shader Simplification</a></li> 
				<li><a href="publication.php?id=lpics05">Lpics: a Hybrid Hardware-Accelerated Relighting Engine for Computer
				Cinematography</a></li> 
				<li><a href="publication.php?id=igids02">Interactive Global Illumination in Dynamic Scenes</a></li> 
			  </ul> 

			  <h3 class="vspace">Efficient rendering of complex appearance</h3> 
	
			  <p class="novspaceafter">High-quality rendering of complex environments remains problematic, especially when complex materials and
			  lighting are involved. I am interested in deriving scalable algorithms for offline rendering of complex
			  appearance in environments with high geometric complexity. I believe these developments will shed insights on
			  how to derive interactive scalable formulations on future machines. Related papers:</p> 
	
			  <ul> 
				<li><a href="publication.php?id=safegi10">SafeGI: Type Checking to Improve Correctness in Rendering System Implementation</a></li> 
				<li><a href="publication.php?id=temporal08">Tensor Clustering for Rendering Many-Light Animations</a></li> 
				<li><a href="publication.php?id=mxsmp07">Matrix Row-Column Sampling for the Many-Light Problem</a></li> 
				<li><a href="publication.php?id=lod05">User-Configurable Automatic Shader Simplification</a></li> 
				<li><a href="publication.php?id=hybrid05">A Hybrid Monte Carlo Method for Accurate and Efficient Subsurface
				Scattering</a></li> 
			  </ul> 

			  <h3 class="vspace">Perceptual metrics for rendering algorithms</h3> 
	
			  <p class="novspaceafter">The basic premise of appearance-based rendering is to avoid computing details of an image that our eyes
			  cannot see. In the past, I have been interested in understanding how perceptual metrics can be used in
			  interactive applications, instead of offline ones. To do so, I have investigated a decision theoretic
			  formulation of interactive rendering, where perceptual metrics are used as priority schemes. Related papers:</p> 
	
			  <ul> 
				<li><a href="publication.php?id=decisiontheory03">Perceptually-Driven Decision Theory for Interactive
				Realistic Rendering</a></li> 
				<li><a href="publication.php?id=fdp03">Functional Difference Predictors (FDPs): measuring meaningful image
				differences</a></li> 
				<li><a href="publication.php?id=textures01">Perceptually-based texture caching for hardware
				rendering</a></li> 
			  </ul> 

			  <h3 class="vspace">Non-photorealistic rendering</h3> 
	
			  <p class="novspaceafter">And finally, as most graphics people, I love artistic renditions. As a side project, I developed a
			  generalized mosaicing algorithm that made the frontispiece for siggraph. Related papers:</p> 
	
			  <ul> 
				<li><a href="publication.php?id=jim02">Jigsaw Image Mosaics</a></li> 
			  </ul> 

